\f0\fs24 \cf0 Abstract/Introduction\
\
This paper is about the value of mindfulness practice in technologically-mediated music making, design, and performance. The multifunctional laptop computer, while alluring, conditions its users towards a propensity for distraction by encouraging off-task activity and multitasking, potentially hindering a focused creative process. This is examined in contrast with a 
\i modular synthesizer
\i0 , an electronic device with a more singular purpose as a musical instrument. Drawing on the course text 
\i How to Cook Your Life,
\i0  the virtue of mindfully attending to one\'92s activity is considered, be it musical as in the case of free-form improvisation, or music-adjacent such as packing up equipment following a performance. The paper concludes on the role of mindful listening in the context of free-form music improvisation. \
\
To begin, this paper is situated within the context of the author\'92s own discipline, that of experimental and electroacoustic music. An electroacoustic composer seeks out novel sounds, and holds a curiosity toward the means of the production of novel sounds, and a desire to experiment with these means and procedures. Often is the case that such procedures are afforded through the development of custom computer software which can manipulate sound to produce ever-interesting sonic results. This practice requires an investment in several disciplines, including knowledge of music, listening skills, improvisation, design, and computational literacy. (diSessa 5) \
\
However, creating music while using a laptop computer can have its deficits, particularly when it comes to sustaining one\'92s attention on a singular task, which stands in opposition to a predominant feature of modern computers: multitasking. According to Jesper Aagaard, \'93multitasking does not in fact denote a quantitative enumeration of tasks, but a qualitative distinction between on- and off-task activity. In other words, multitasking is functionally equivalent to distraction.\'94 (
\i Multitasking as Distraction: A Conceptual Analysis of Media Multitasking Research 
\i0 1) The propensity of computer usage in music-making towards multitasking runs counter to a mindful approach to creativity. While learning how to program affords the opportunity to create instruments capable of realizing novel compositional ideas, the increased engagement with a computer often means that it is increasingly difficult to remain present and focused as a listener. This challenge is intensified when the electroacoustic musician plays instruments which they had designed: during an improvisation \'97 or even practising at home \'97 when encountering a new limitation in what the instrument is capable of, they so often became distracted by immediately excitedly thinking about the addition of new modifications, something to change in the instrument, that they would abandon their playing to set off making those modifications. Hours would pass and the activity and intention was no longer about music making, but instead consumed by design thinking. As the degree to which one is focused does not change, the satisfaction experienced from the activity feels similar. \
At first, programming \'97 a creative act unto itself \'97 feels like playing music, but without listening involved. Without intentionally setting one\'92s mind on to the singular focus of playing an instrument, and acknowledging and declining urges to switch to an off-task such as programming, one can become disillusioned toward computer-mediated music performance because it seemingly begins to encompass more than playing the instrument. This tendency toward distracted use of technology is consistent with contemporary educational research on attention in computationally-mediated classrooms, in which students have been documented succumbing to the \'93\'85temptation to engage in off-task activity [and that this is] a pre-reflective attraction towards frequently visited, educationally unrelated websites.\'94 (
\i Drawn to Distraction: A Qualitative Study of Off-Task use of Educational Technology 
\i0 93)\
\
Post-phenomenology is useful in the context of human-computer interaction, and its notions of 
\i multistability 
\i0 and 
\i embodiment
\i0  (
\i Drawn to Distraction
\i0  91) are salient to a discussion of mindfulness and creativity in the context of technologically mediated art. Post-phenomenology dispatches with the notion of a technology\'92s essence, and through the notion of multistability describes a particular technology\'92s identity as contingent upon how it is used, (\'93Bodies in Technology\'94 70) and in the case of a laptop computer, multistability has regularly become a targeted design pattern. (
\i Can Continental Philosophy Deal with the New Technologies? 
\i0 326) In other words, a laptop possesses such stabilities as a writing tool, musical instrument, and movie player, etc. \
\
When engaging in musical improvisation with a custom digital musical instrument on a laptop, given either their potential multistabilities, one is subjected to multiple sources of distraction. In the case of a digital musical instrument, improvisation leads one to experiment with the affordances and constraints of the system, yet rather than keeping this exploration contained within manual operation of the instrument, often one\'92s attention gives way to an instinct to stop playing and modify its structure in realtime \'97 make edits to its code \'97 which is a music-adjacent activity. In the case of the laptop with its \'93\'85sources of [cognitive] overload and distraction \'85 [such as] the orientation and visual nature of laptops, along with pop-ups, instant messages, movement and lighting of text, and even things like low-battery warnings, make laptops inherently distracting. (Bhave 2002; Melerdiercks 2005; Wickets & Hollands 2002)\'94 (Fried 908)\
\
Post-phenomenology is also informed by \'93\'85embodied relations to material technologies.\'94 (
\i Drawn to Distraction 
\i0 91) Given a particular technology\'92s multistability, one performs different actions in order to successfully use the technology in different ways: an acoustic guitar can be used as a melodic instrument, but also as a hand drum. Rosenberger terms these actions 
\i relational strategies
\i0 , contingent upon a human performer\'92s manual handling of the technology they are what constrain a technology to a particular stability. (Rosenberger 176) \
\
When compared to a computer, an acoustic instrument may have multiple stabilities, but there are no computer screens nor alerts to draw one\'92s attention away from sound and musical creativity. A guitar will remain a guitar regardless of what modifications are envisioned. An instrument which has an open amount of stabilities and encourages re-configuration of its system, yet constrains its purpose towards music making is a special type of electronic instrument called a hardware modular synthesizer. Its uniqueness as an instrument is that it is an analog computer whose components are left partially disconnected, allowing for the player to partially reshape the function and behaviour of the machine by creating temporary electrical connections, called 
\i patches,
\i0  between these components. In this regard, the act of playing a modular synthesizer is similar to the practice of live coding (Hutchins 147) which is the on-stage performance practice of programming code which generates live music. In other words, learning to play an instrument whose musical affordances and constraints may be defined and redefined during performance meant that a passion for design thinking can be legitimately incorporated within a real-time musical practice. In the case of laptop-based music making, the impulse to reprogram a system would require a shift in focus, attention, and intention such that the result would not only be less musical, but due to the split in attention the ears would not be discerning of such output, and the player would also be subject to further potential distraction in the form of notifications, whereas with the modular synthesizer the mind and focus is bound by the sound being generated contemporaneously, and bound by an intention to explore this sound through the continual retuning of the system. \
\
Performing with a hardware modular synthesizer is a highly embodied, first-person experience. The act of controlling such a device \'97 its relational strategy \'97 is contingent on gestures specific to the tactile affordances of physical knobs, switches, and patching. This is contrasted in the case of laptop-based digital musical instruments by the fact that the control data generated from the more multistable mouse and keyboard are mapped onto the musical parameters. In either case, the understanding of the state of the instrument is informed partially by the visible interface, and partially in the imagination.\
\
On the morning of April 9\super th\nosupersub  the author presented on K\uc0\u333 sh\u333  Uchiyama R\u333 shi\'92s book 
\i How to Cook Your Life: from the Zen Kitchen to Enlightenment
\i0  (Dogen, Wright, Uchiyama 2005)
\i , 
\i0 one of the assigned readings for the course 
\i Introduction to Mindfulness: Understanding and Using Mindfulness in the Professions
\i0 . Throughout the reading of the book, it was apparent that the discussion around the path of the Tenzo Kyokun and \'93\'85his pursuit of the Way\'94 (Dogen 3), could serve as allegorical to the experience of a life dedicated to exploring sound, such as the author of this paper \'97 a composer and musician \'97 has, and so it was decided that the presentation would be designed to incorporate and heighten awareness of the sounds of the classroom, including for example, the persistent din of the HVAC system. The composer\'92s primary instrument \'97 a synthesizer \'97 was also prepared for the class as an accompaniment alongside the soundscape of the room. Doing so was intended to foreground the considerable responsibility of having some influence over the sonic environment of the room such that it could provide space for breath, thought, and yet also modulate class members\'92 mindfulness by periodically introducing moments of novelty. (Langer and Moldoveanu 1) \
\
The author conducted a one hour yoga practice before sunrise and then arrived on campus an hour before class. In the time before class, the synthesizer patch was constructed for the class, iteratively prepared from a blank state (no patch connections). How this was conducted was designed to be aligned with a mindful approach as per the preparing of rice, as was insisted upon by Tenzo Kyokun in 
