Gentle deliberation was paid to the handling and interaction with each module, cable, and accessory belonging to the modular synthesizer. The emphasis with which Tenzo Kyokun placed upon the care and attention to finest detail when washing rice was particularly instructive: a modular synthesizer, though its chassis is made of metals and fastened with screws, is nevertheless a rather delicate electrical apparatus susceptible to damage from falls, and moisture. Great care must also be taken when unpacking this instrument from its case. As it is an electronic instrument, the question of how to safely store cables and other accessories is paramount, as is their subsequent retrieval at a later time. Often, items such as cables are layered upon each other, and so it is important when reaching for one or more cables that one is aware of how many cables they are clutching, and that the whole of the cable may be freely drawn from the case without snagging or pulling on other items in its vicinity. Cables are colour-coded according to their length. A well maintained collection of cables will also include cable ties \'97 20-30cm lengths of string or velcro straps \'97 for each cable. These are used to secure a cable in its coiled form, and will also prevent it from becoming tangled with other cables. Failure to adhere to the use of cable ties has as its consequences lost time due to untangling, and potential damage to the integrity of the cable\'92s construction. Cable ties should already be secured to a fixed point somewhere along the cable, usually close to one of the ends, such that they do not become displaced when their cable is uncoiled, nor lost between the stages of unpacking and packing. \
 Equally important is the act of tidying one\'92s music equipment following the conclusion of a session or performance. A proper method of cable wrapping takes effort, concentration, and tactile sensing, and is necessary to ensure both longevity of use and effectiveness. One holds an end of a cable in one hand, and with their thumb, fore and middle fingers on the other hand, gently pinches the cable about an arm\'92s length away from the same end, and pulls that point of the cable towards the first hand, gently twisting the cable in what feels like the direction it wants to turn, resulting in a single loop. Continue with this gesture but be aware of the direction that the cable wants to twist: twisting it in one direction will come at a greater ease than the other. The cable should not be made to wrap around one\'92s elbow and shoulder, as this stretches the interior wires and compromises the protective exterior coating. One can verify that care was taken to properly coil a cable by holding one of the ends in one hand, and tossing the entire loop forward in front of oneself. When thrown in this manner, a correctly coiled cable will spill out in an even trajectory, whereas an uneven one will get caught on itself, or twist and land in ways unpleasing to the eye. The sound of a correctly coiled cable unfolding along a surface in the correct way is a satisfying sounding 
\i klaaattt
\i0 . When put to use again later on, a correctly coiled cable will also be amenable to its desired placement in a space, whereas a cable that was coiled hastily and without regard for its natural twist will be much harder to lay down flat, and therefore will require more effort to ensure that it is not a tripping hazard. When the cable has been fully coiled, locate its tie and secure its loop with a single, tight the bow such that it does not untie in storage or during travel.\
\
