One element common to both cooking and playing music is time, and more specifically ephemerality. If food begins to brown and dry out, water can be added to compensate for some properties, such as moisture, to begin to bring it away from further charring, but it will never be quite the same as it was before. A hardware modular synthesizer, being a machine with no stored memory and unlike its software-based counterparts, is one in which changes cannot be precisely undone. These constraints are partly what contributes to a liveness in either activity, but more important is that no thing will remain in its state forever, evoking what professor Orr referred to as \'93\'85the fundamental delusion [being] the one of the reified self. We think we are going to last forever.\'94 (Orr)\
\
In the case of musical free improvisation play, the key elements here are that there is mutual influence: players control the output of their instruments, but their positions relative to each other and relative to their acoustic space will condition how and what they hear. Similarly,  \'93\'85the means whereby we turn things even while simultaneously we are being turned by them\'85\'94 (Dogen 7) \
This is further evoked by the Tenzo\'92s discussion of two people beholding the same cup, that two musicians may be hearing the same sound, but will listen to them differently. \
